<br>
Reasons for this are:<br>
No moving parts, ergo fewer hardware failures<br>
Less electricity usage<br>
Less noise<br>
Less heat<br>
Little to no upgrades<br>
No pesky open ports, ergo less hacking<br>
<br>
I could probably come up with more reasons, but that is all just right off hand.<br>
<br>
Hubs can not route.  They are simply "splitters"... no intelligence (unless you're talking about a switch, that's a different story, but still not technically classified as a router though they can do some layer 2 "routing").<br>
<br>
If you have a hub, you still have to have something that can route, be it a router or a machine acting as a router/gateway/proxy.<br>
<br>
So, if you're going to have a machine that is going to be your gateway to the internet, it's best to have a dedicated machine.  Mainly because if this machine crashes or is rebooted, it's going to kill Internet access to everyone/thing that goes through it.  With a dedicated machine, the idea is, nothing is happening on it, therefore it never needs to be rebooted.<br>
<br>
And of course, if you're going to have a machine acting as a router, then you need to reread the first paragraph of my post. :)<br>
<br>
Of course, that's just my opinion and personal preference. <p>- Kraphalis 53 Vicar<br>
