<br>
I have also run 5 PCs simultaneously playing Counter-Strike and had good connections with this setup. (I have a 1mb DSL line.) For all intents and purposes, I have a seperate connection with this setup. <br>
<br>
Since the router is a hardware firewall, I dont have much of a security problem for what I am doing. (I suspect that a dedicated hacker could get thru it, but for what purpose?) And if I really want to be secure, I can add a software firewall between the router and the network if I really want to.<br>
<br>
The only real draw back that I have seen is my CS server was not registering with WON. So while I could have an internet game running, it was not visible on the list there. I think I have figured out how to work around this, but haven't had time to try yet.<br>
<br>
The drawback to running a linux box is that I dont know much about it. I have it installed on one of the hard drives on my system (Mandrake 8.0) but havent explored the opportunities much. I looked at using Windows Internet Connection Sharing, but have heard mixed reviews. At the time it was 20-30$ to buy a new NIC or ~100$ or so for the single port router that plugged into my hub... I sprung for the extra cash to hopefully make my life easier. So far, I have been very happy with the purchase. <br>
<br>
E.<br>
